00:00:00,350 --> 00:00:04,410
So far we've covered how to
start a new spreadsheet,

2
00:00:04,410 --> 00:00:06,150
enter in data, and make it look

3
00:00:06,150 --> 00:00:09,180
refined and ready for
some serious analysis.

4
00:00:09,180 --> 00:00:10,830
Now we'll learn how to perform

5
00:00:10,830 --> 00:00:12,755
calculations in your spreadsheet.

6
00:00:12,755 --> 00:00:14,820
You may need to
calculate everything

7
00:00:14,820 --> 00:00:16,830
from sums to averages,

8
00:00:16,830 --> 00:00:19,755
to finding minimum
and maximum amounts.

9
00:00:19,755 --> 00:00:21,300
You'll use calculations for

10
00:00:21,300 --> 00:00:23,460
a lot of different
kinds of tasks.

11
00:00:23,460 --> 00:00:26,655
In this video, we'll focus
on learning the basics

12
00:00:26,655 --> 00:00:28,320
and then do a little math with

13
00:00:28,320 --> 00:00:30,345
some sales data to practice.

14
00:00:30,345 --> 00:00:32,440
Let's talk about formulas first.

15
00:00:32,440 --> 00:00:35,090
You might remember that
a formula is a set of

16
00:00:35,090 --> 00:00:38,375
instructions that perform
a specific calculation.

17
00:00:38,375 --> 00:00:41,395
Basically, formulas can
do the math for you.

18
00:00:41,395 --> 00:00:43,460
Now, they don't only do math,

19
00:00:43,460 --> 00:00:45,230
they can do a lot more.

20
00:00:45,230 --> 00:00:47,690
Soon you'll learn
different ways you can use

21
00:00:47,690 --> 00:00:50,375
them throughout the data
analysis processes.

22
00:00:50,375 --> 00:00:53,870
Formulas are built on operators
which are symbols that

23
00:00:53,870 --> 00:00:55,490
name the type of operation or

24
00:00:55,490 --> 00:00:57,455
calculation to be performed.

25
00:00:57,455 --> 00:01:01,160
For example, a plus sign
is a common operator.

26
00:01:01,160 --> 00:01:03,770
The formulas you use
as a data analyst will

27
00:01:03,770 --> 00:01:06,455
usually include at
least one operator.

28
00:01:06,455 --> 00:01:09,515
Now, let's talk about math
expressions or equations.

29
00:01:09,515 --> 00:01:11,900
These can take a lot
of different forms,

30
00:01:11,900 --> 00:01:14,555
but you might be familiar
with them already.

31
00:01:14,555 --> 00:01:22,845
3 minus 1, 15 plus 8 divided
by 2, 846 times 513.

32
00:01:22,845 --> 00:01:25,325
These are all examples
of expressions.

33
00:01:25,325 --> 00:01:28,015
Is this bringing back
memories of grade school?

34
00:01:28,015 --> 00:01:29,945
Well, back in math class,

35
00:01:29,945 --> 00:01:32,690
you most likely learned to
complete an expression by

36
00:01:32,690 --> 00:01:35,585
including an equal
sign and the solution.

37
00:01:35,585 --> 00:01:37,985
It's slightly different
with spreadsheets.

38
00:01:37,985 --> 00:01:39,710
When you create a formula using

39
00:01:39,710 --> 00:01:41,659
an expression in a spreadsheet,

40
00:01:41,659 --> 00:01:44,465
you start the formula
with an equal sign.

41
00:01:44,465 --> 00:01:46,820
For example, if we
want to subtract,

42
00:01:46,820 --> 00:01:49,490
we type an equal sign
followed by the rest of

43
00:01:49,490 --> 00:01:53,410
the expression without any
spaces in the formula.

44
00:01:53,410 --> 00:01:55,500
Now let's try an expression

45
00:01:55,500 --> 00:01:57,300
that's a bit more challenging.

46
00:01:57,300 --> 00:02:02,540
We'll type 31982, then

47
00:02:02,540 --> 00:02:08,940
a hyphen for a minus
sign, then 17795.

48
00:02:08,940 --> 00:02:12,000
To calculate, we press "Enter."

49
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:13,610
You'll most likely use

50
00:02:13,610 --> 00:02:15,320
formulas this way
when dealing with

51
00:02:15,320 --> 00:02:19,099
large numbers or expressions
with multiple steps.

52
00:02:19,099 --> 00:02:22,430
Here are the operators you
will use to complete formulas.

53
00:02:22,430 --> 00:02:24,200
The plus sign for addition,

54
00:02:24,200 --> 00:02:26,750
the minus or hyphen
for subtraction,

55
00:02:26,750 --> 00:02:28,865
the asterisk for multiplication,

56
00:02:28,865 --> 00:02:31,570
and the forward
slash for division.

57
00:02:31,570 --> 00:02:34,190
The division and
multiplication symbols

58
00:02:34,190 --> 00:02:36,380
might be different than
what you're used to.

59
00:02:36,380 --> 00:02:39,190
Small changes, but
important to keep in mind.

60
00:02:39,190 --> 00:02:41,660
If you already have data
in your spreadsheet,

61
00:02:41,660 --> 00:02:44,780
you can use cell references
in your formulas instead.

62
00:02:44,780 --> 00:02:47,630
A cell reference is
a single cell or

63
00:02:47,630 --> 00:02:48,680
range of cells in

64
00:02:48,680 --> 00:02:51,305
a worksheet that can
be used in a formula.

65
00:02:51,305 --> 00:02:53,600
Cell references
contain the letter of

66
00:02:53,600 --> 00:02:56,570
the column and the number of
the row where the data is.

67
00:02:56,570 --> 00:02:59,365
A range of cells is a
collection of two or more cells.

68
00:02:59,365 --> 00:03:02,990
A range can include cells
from the same row or column,

69
00:03:02,990 --> 00:03:05,810
or from different columns
and rows collected together.

70
00:03:05,810 --> 00:03:08,810
We'll show you an example
in an upcoming video.

71
00:03:08,810 --> 00:03:12,070
Now let's apply what we just
learned to some sales data.

72
00:03:12,070 --> 00:03:14,360
If we want to add
these figures to find

73
